    <div>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What is a Roth conversion? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>A Roth conversion involves moving money from a traditional IRA or 401(k) to a Roth IRA. You pay taxes on the converted amount now, but all future growth and withdrawals in retirement are tax-free.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Who benefits most from Roth conversions? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>High earners in their 50s and 60s who expect to be in the same or higher tax bracket in retirement, have time for tax-free growth, and want to reduce future required minimum distributions.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">When is the best time to do Roth conversions? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>The best time is typically during lower-income years (early retirement, market downturns, or gaps between jobs) when you can convert at lower tax rates. We analyze your specific situation to find optimal timing.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">How much should I convert each year? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>The optimal amount depends on your current tax bracket, future income projections, and retirement timeline. We typically recommend staying within your current bracket or converting up to the next bracket ceiling.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Can I undo a Roth conversion? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>No, Roth conversions became permanent starting in 2018. That's why proper planning and analysis before converting is crucial to avoid costly mistakes.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Do I have to pay taxes immediately on a Roth conversion? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Yes, you'll owe taxes on the converted amount in the year you convert. We help you plan for the tax impact and coordinate with your overall tax strategy.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">How much should I convert to Roth each year? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>The goal is to fill your current tax bracket without pushing into the next one. For married filing jointly couples in the 22% bracket, this typically means converting $40,000-$80,000 per year. We model your specific income and deductions to find the optimal conversion amount each year.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Is it too late to do Roth conversions in my 70s? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Not necessarily. Converting in your 70s can still reduce future RMDs, lower IRMAA surcharges on Medicare premiums, and create a tax-free inheritance for your heirs. The analysis shifts from personal tax savings to legacy and Medicare cost reduction.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Do Roth conversions affect my Social Security? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Roth conversions have no direct effect on your Social Security benefit amount. However, the converted amount increases your Modified Adjusted Gross Income (MAGI), which can increase the taxation of your Social Security benefits (up to 85% taxable) and trigger IRMAA surcharges on Medicare premiums two years later.</p></div>
      </button>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

